00:07:00.750 --> 00:07:07.480
I want to draw back 20
years almost to the day,

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:15.640
almost exactly 20 years ago, I
was in Dushanbe and the civil war

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:21.950
in Tajikistan was nearing its end
but you could still hear shooting.

00:07:21.950 --> 00:07:28.170
And the city was really kind of
a depressing mess at that time.

00:07:28.170 --> 00:07:35.360
Everyone was very fearful and
then suddenly in the midst

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:44.760
of this rather gloomy civil war
situation, three soldiers marched

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:53.270
down the street with a flag and I
looked, that's-- what's that flag?

00:07:53.270 --> 00:07:54.570
I've never seen it before.

00:07:54.570 --> 00:07:56.890
It was new.

00:07:56.890 --> 00:08:01.240
And they said, well-- I caught
up with them and asked them

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:04.140
and they said, well
that's our new flag.

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:07.360
And I looked at it,
I was very curios.

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:09.500
It's first time I've ever seen it.

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:12.890
I noticed there is a green on it.

00:08:12.890 --> 00:08:15.880
And he said, oh yeah, that
refers to the mountains,

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:20.510
green or to the green valleys and
so on where everything is growing.

00:08:20.510 --> 00:08:23.150
And I said, and it's
white, what about that?

00:08:23.150 --> 00:08:25.360
And they said, well, the
white is the mountains,

00:08:25.360 --> 00:08:27.010
of course, snowy mountains.

00:08:27.010 --> 00:08:32.630
And the red, he said well
that's the life of the people.

00:08:32.630 --> 00:08:38.020 position:56%
I thought, gee, that's unfortunate
color for the time of the civil war.

00:08:38.020 --> 00:08:42.260 position:56%
But there was also on this new flag,

00:08:42.260 --> 00:08:47.670
there were I think
seven stars and a crown.

00:08:47.670 --> 00:08:51.900
So I asked, what are the
seven stars refer to?

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:53.510
And they didn't know.

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:56.180
And I said, well who
designed the flag?

00:08:56.180 --> 00:08:59.080
They-- oh, we can take you to him.

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:01.310
He's just a few blocks away.

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:08.000
It turns out it was designed
by a Lithuanian Catholic

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.450
who had an antique store, an
old book and antique store right

00:09:12.450 --> 00:09:14.810
in the center of Dushanbe.

00:09:14.810 --> 00:09:18.410
And so I went in and met
this man very hospitable,

00:09:18.410 --> 00:09:22.940
very interesting man and he
indeed had designed the flag.

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:25.650
So I said, what about the stars?

00:09:25.650 --> 00:09:33.210
And he said, well he said when I
was a boy, a student in Lithuania,

00:09:33.210 --> 00:09:42.760
I had to study a work of German
literature, [inaudible] and he said

00:09:42.760 --> 00:09:51.490
that was about Persian poetry,
a Hafez mainly as you know.

00:09:51.490 --> 00:10:00.060
And he said, I then got interested
and looked around and it turns

00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:02.480
out there were other poets.

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:10.250 position:56%
And-- in Persian, but he said once I
was focusing on designing the flag.

00:10:10.250 --> 00:10:14.730
I asked, who were these other
poets that I learned about?

00:10:14.730 --> 00:10:21.200
And he got the whole list you
know, Ferdowsi, Rabi'a Balkhi

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:23.740
and [inaudible] and many others.

00:10:23.740 --> 00:10:27.140
And he looked into it.

00:10:27.140 --> 00:10:30.930
He didn't know anything
about this, and he said that,

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:34.310
my goodness they are all from here.

00:10:34.310 --> 00:10:40.100
And he meant Central Asia and, of
course, Tajikistan particularly

00:10:40.100 --> 00:10:45.220
but somewhere from like Rabi'a
Balkhi, she's obviously from Balkh.

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:48.010
But they were from
the East if you will.

00:10:48.010 --> 00:10:52.210
And he said, so I decided
to put them all on the flag.

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:55.500
And I don't know which
specific poets this reflect--

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:59.080
stars refer to, but it's
a very interesting--

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:04.860
it struck me as very interesting
that these figures whom one thinks

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:09.920
of as core figures of
Persian culture and literature

00:11:09.920 --> 00:11:13.250
and poetry are actually
from something

00:11:13.250 --> 00:11:16.580
that geographically is
not part of Iran today.

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:21.170
Well, that's not quite true
because the eastern edge of Iran

00:11:21.170 --> 00:11:27.510
as you know, Khorasan, Ferdowsi
was from there for example.

00:11:27.510 --> 00:11:33.990
But the fact is that
this extraordinary bond

00:11:33.990 --> 00:11:39.100
of poetic geniuses came from
the Central Asian territory.

00:11:39.100 --> 00:11:43.010
And this got me thinking,
well, who else is from there?

00:11:43.010 --> 00:11:50.050
And I-- this 20-- 18 years later
I published a 650-page book

00:11:50.050 --> 00:11:52.010 position:56%
which is an answer to that question.

00:11:52.010 --> 00:11:55.850
Who else is from there and why?

00:11:55.850 --> 00:12:01.360
Why did that happen, you know,
that these geniuses that showed

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:05.920
up from what we now call
Central Asia defined broadly?

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:13.730
Well, let me note that I
also knew nothing about this,

00:12:13.730 --> 00:12:17.240
learned about other
Persianate languages.

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:24.460
You know, like Bactriane, like
Sogdiane, Khwarazmian so on which--

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:31.160
I mean, Khawarazmian, we know
from their greatest figure,

00:12:31.160 --> 00:12:36.060
the great scientist Biruni about
whom I'll say something more later.

00:12:36.060 --> 00:12:40.420
We know he wrote about this
thousand years ago that this--

00:12:40.420 --> 00:12:46.640
an entire literature was
destroyed and Khwarazmian Persian,

00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:50.560
when the Arabs came
through after the--

00:12:50.560 --> 00:12:53.390
in the Muslim conquest
of the region,

00:12:53.390 --> 00:12:55.550
he says that the entire literature,

00:12:55.550 --> 00:13:00.210
whole library after
library was obliterated.

00:13:00.210 --> 00:13:03.630
So, we basically--
everything I'm talking

00:13:03.630 --> 00:13:07.470
about is a fragment
of what once existed.

00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:13.890 position:56%
And all the people I'm about to talk
about why we know about them mainly

00:13:13.890 --> 00:13:18.270
through a fragment of their
total works, all right.

00:13:18.270 --> 00:13:22.210
No writer, no scientist,
no mathematician,

00:13:22.210 --> 00:13:25.900
no theologian, no philosopher,
whoever.

00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:35.350
Do we have more than maybe 10, 15
at most 20% of what they wrote?

00:13:35.350 --> 00:13:37.120
The rest is lost.

00:13:37.120 --> 00:13:41.610
So everything I'm about to
speak about you have to multiply

00:13:41.610 --> 00:13:45.970
if what we know is
based on that 20%.

00:13:45.970 --> 00:13:49.010
You have to multiply it by five.

00:13:49.010 --> 00:13:51.640
And by the way, what is preserved

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:55.270
and what isn't preserved
is often quite propitious

00:13:55.270 --> 00:13:58.680
because we know the names
of some of the hundreds

00:13:58.680 --> 00:14:01.400
and hundreds of lost works.

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:05.650
Now, let me therefore begin

00:14:05.650 --> 00:14:10.190
by introducing three
quite different figures.

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:16.670 position:56%
The first-- and I'll introduce them
not because they're the biggest fish

00:14:16.670 --> 00:14:20.750
in the pond, but because they
are representative of the kind

00:14:20.750 --> 00:14:27.400
of geniuses that this region
produced from roughly the 8th

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:30.050
through the 12th centuries AD.

00:14:30.050 --> 00:14:33.390
And let me start with al-Khwarizmi.

00:14:34.450 --> 00:14:36.350
He-- you know him.

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:41.510 position:56%
In fact, you used his name
probably in the last couple of weeks

00:14:41.510 --> 00:14:45.410
in English without
knowing it because you--

00:14:45.410 --> 00:14:48.130
someone was telling
you about the algorithm

00:14:48.130 --> 00:14:52.810
on which some computer
process is based.

00:14:52.810 --> 00:14:55.810
Well, that is a distortion

00:14:55.810 --> 00:15:01.260
of his name al-Khwarizmi it's
transliterated into Russian

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:04.370
which is not quite
right but al-Khwarizmi.

00:15:04.370 --> 00:15:10.300
And when he's book was
translated, his book on algebra,

00:15:10.300 --> 00:15:16.680
the title is Algebra by the way,
when he-- it has a subtitle,

00:15:16.680 --> 00:15:21.440
a compendious book on calculations
by completion and balancing.

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:25.960
When this book, Algebra, was
translated it immediately

00:15:25.960 --> 00:15:29.970
into Latin, it became
the standard work.

00:15:29.970 --> 00:15:40.020
And, of course, people wondered
who is this author, al-Khwarizmi?

00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:43.740
Well, they think-- they didn't
know much anything about him,

00:15:43.740 --> 00:15:48.430
but they did know he was a very big
figure in the world of mathematics

00:15:48.430 --> 00:15:53.780
and therefore anyone who was, you
know, this was formal compliment.

00:15:53.780 --> 00:15:57.000
Anyone who was a great
mathematician,

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:03.690
they called in medieval Europe an
al-Khwarizmi and hence algorithm.

00:16:03.690 --> 00:16:07.560
It's part of our culture.

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:14.510
He also, by the way, he had in
his spare time invented linear

00:16:14.510 --> 00:16:20.300
and quadratic equations, worked
out sine and cosine functions.

00:16:20.300 --> 00:16:25.550
He also pioneered in the
field of trigonometry.

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:29.810
And what he did basically
was to pick

00:16:29.810 --> 00:16:34.950
up from the Greeks what they had
done in these mathematical fields

00:16:34.950 --> 00:16:37.760
and pushed it way beyond.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:41.240
Why did he know about the Greeks?

00:16:41.240 --> 00:16:44.350
Because Syrian Christians
who knew Arabic

00:16:44.350 --> 00:16:49.740
and knew Greek were translating
these works and they--

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:53.160
but there are a lot of Syrian
Christians out in Central Asia.

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:56.260
And so, these works
were known out there.

00:16:56.260 --> 00:16:59.700
So, he also did a lot
of work in astronomy.

00:16:59.700 --> 00:17:03.450
He did astronomical tables
that were based on the kind

00:17:03.450 --> 00:17:08.100
of astronomical tables they were
doing in India at this time.

00:17:08.100 --> 00:17:10.590
He also, by the way
speaking of India,

00:17:10.590 --> 00:17:15.120
wrote a book in-- on
Indian numerals.

00:17:15.120 --> 00:17:19.820
Now, Indian numerals, do
you mean Arabic numerals?

00:17:19.820 --> 00:17:25.320
No. Indian numerals, because he
wrote that book on Indian numerals,

00:17:25.320 --> 00:17:32.110
Arabs picked it up and by the
time this numeral system arrived

00:17:32.110 --> 00:17:35.860
in the west, they knew
only is Arabic numerals.

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:40.830
But you could just as well call
them Central Asian numerals.

00:17:40.830 --> 00:17:46.640
But he was a formidable figure
in other words, al-Khwarizmi.

00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:54.590 position:56%
And just to remind you its dates are
7 AD to 850, that's a long time ago

00:17:54.590 --> 00:17:56.890
to be doing such genius work.

00:17:56.890 --> 00:18:03.170
Then my second figure is from
what is now Southern Kazakhstan.

00:18:03.170 --> 00:18:08.970
He-- this is on the great
northern route across east-west.

00:18:08.970 --> 00:18:13.080
It's pretty much the route that
this new so-called Silk Roads

00:18:13.080 --> 00:18:14.450
